observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct, require timelines and monitor the compliance of the Inventory Committee with the guidelines and procedures in inventory taking and disposition of non-existing PPE items for one-time cleansing of PPE as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006, specifically the following activities:

prepare and complete the Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) containing the specific assignments/duties of the Committee members, the cut-off date, and a schedule specifying the dates and locations of the inventory taking activities from start, up to the targeted completion of 

physical inventory;

submit the approved PIP to the COA Audit Team at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory taking activities;

conduct the inventory taking activities in accordance with the PIP, ensuring all necessary information such as the cost and specific identifiers like the dates and property numbers of the properties are indicated, using the prescribed forms, of all properties of the Municipality over a three-month period;

prepare the RPCPPE upon completion of the physical count, adopting the uniform property identification system for PPE, showing complete data and clustered by PPE type, and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant for reconcilliaton and to the Audit Team on or before December 29, 2023.

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant prepare an adjusting entry to derecognize from the PPE accounts the items with acquisition cost below the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00 and issue the corresponding Inventory Custodian Slip.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

prepare the necessary adjusting entry to reclassify from Due to NGAs account the amount of ₱1,586,969.00 to Trust Liabilities account in the Trust Fund;

prepare the Disbursement Voucher for the transfer of the total amount of P305,520.22 to the General Fund bank account to reclassify the  funds from Due to NGAs account to Government Equity and inform the Municipal Budget Officer of the funds available for appropriation.

We reiterated our recommendation for the Municipal Mayor to issue a written directive, with timelines and sanctions, compelling the Inventory Committee, to perform and complete the following tasks in CY 2024, and monitor their compliance thereon:
Accomplish and complete the comprehensive physical count of all properties owned by the Municipality;
Prepare the RPCPPE in the prescribed form, with each PPE properly classified as to serviceable and unserviceable, with proper identification of persons accountable, status of serviceability and location for immediate submission to the Municipal Accountant before the yearend closing of the LGU books of accounts; and
conduct an investigation on non-existing/missing PPEs and prepare a separate report thereon for immediate submission to the Municipal Accountant as a pre-requisite for the filing of the request for derecognition.
We also reiterated our recommendation for the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjusting entries to reclassify from the PPE accounts the items with unit cost below the ₱50,000.00 threshold totaling ₱869,805.00 to the appropriate account supported with Inventory Custodian Slips;
Lastly, we recommended that the Property Officer and the Municipal Accountant maintain, and update monthly, Property Stock Cards and PPE Ledger Cards, respectively, for each category of assets.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Prepare the Demand Letters, for signature of the Municipal Mayor,  addressed to the Punong Barangays who received the financial assistance requiring their submission of the Report of Checks Issued (RCI) and the Report of Disbursements (RD) on the utilization of the funds they received from the LGU;

Monitor the submission of the required reports from the recipient barangays and record the related expenses upon receipt thereof; and

1. conduct immediately an inspection of all buildings and infrastructure assets, including every road networks, owned by the Municipality and assess its present value and remaining useful life;
2. prepare a report thereon with complete description of the buildings and infrastructure assets and submit the report to the Municipal Accountant before the end of CY 2021.
3. We further recommended that the Municipal Accountant compute and record the monthly depreciation of each depreciable asset under the account Property, Plant and Equipment in order to reflect in the books the correct carrying amount of PPEs. Use the report of the Municipal Engineer in computing the depreciation of buildings and infrastructure assets.

